{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"# Committed store compatibility record with a fail-closed capability gate\n\nIntroduce a committed store-level compatibility record (`format_version` +\n`required_capabilities`) that a v1.0 binary reads before any mutating or\nexternally-publishing operation, failing closed on an unknown version or required\ncapability while keeping reads and diagnostics available. (Readiness Finding 2 —\nverified VALID against `src/rebar/_store/ensures.py`, `src/rebar/reducer/_version.py`,\n`src/rebar/_commands/{compact,fsck,init}.py`, `docs/migrations.md`.)\n\n## Why\n\nrebar's migration mechanism is an idempotent desired-state ensure-registry, not an\nordered ledger: `run_ensures` runs every unit under the write lock, converts\nexceptions to `failed`, and **returns normally** (`src/rebar/_store/ensures.py`\ndocstring \"Never raises\"; init/boot never abort). Event compatibility is\npreserve-and-ignore: unknown event types are skipped in replay\n(`reducer/_replay.py:195-196`) and omitted from the compaction fold but kept on\ndisk (`_commands/compact.py:179-195`), and `fsck` emits an informational WARN that\ndoes not increment `issue_count` or stop operation (`_commands/fsck.py:229-252`,\nwhich itself notes \"a reconcile host on an old binary may push stale state\").\n\nThis forward-compat is correct for *optional additive* data — it prevents an old\ncompactor from deleting new bytes. But there is **no committed store-format-version\nor required-capability record** (confirmed absent; `SCHEMA_VERSION` is a stamp,\nnever compared to fail closed). So an old binary computes state that omits the\nunknown event and can then emit a new event, compact, evaluate close/verify policy,\nor push a stale field to Jira from that incomplete state. `docs/migrations.md`\nexplicitly files the \"A-tier ledger + committed store-format version that fails\nclosed\" under future work. **The reader must ship in v1.0**: an already-installed\nv1.0 binary cannot be taught later to inspect a record whose existence and\nsemantics were not defined in v1.0 — so to ever mark a store as requiring a\npost-v1.0 capability, v1.0 must already know how to detect and refuse unknown\nrequired capabilities.\n\n## What\n\nAdopt git's repository-format-version pattern\n(`core.repositoryformatversion` + `extensions.*`: an implementation that does not\nunderstand the advertised format or a required extension must not operate, because\ncontinuing can produce incorrect results or lose data), and git's staged rollout\n(teach readers first, make writing opt-in, default later):\n\n- Add a committed store-level record, minimally:\n  `{\"format_version\": 1, \"required_capabilities\": []}`.\n- **Absent-record (pre-v1.0 store) policy — expand phase.** Every store created by a\n  pre-v1.0 build has no record. Treat an **absent** record as the implicit legacy\n  format (version 0, compatible / pass-through), and have the idempotent\n  ensure-registry (School B) write the record at the current version on the next\n  covered write / init / fsck-repair / MCP-boot. So: **absent = legacy, needs\n  migration, NOT blocked**; **present but incompatible = blocked (fail-closed)**.\n  This makes upgrade-in-place work with no manual step and no data loss for existing\n  development users. (Follows git's staged \"teach readers first\" rollout and an\n  expand-contract migration shape.)\n- **Rollback safety.** A rollback to a pre-v1.0 binary must leave the store operable:\n  the record file must be an *ignored-unknown* file to old binaries (it must not be\n  parsed-and-errored, and must not interact destructively with old-binary compaction\n  / fsck). Confirm and document this so rollback is safe (or document a\n  compensating-forward path if it is not).\n- Add a compatibility check that runs **before** any operation that mutates the\n  store or publishes derived state: event append, transition, claim, compaction /\n  snapshot rebuild, delete, archive, Jira push / reconcile, MCP write tools,\n  automatic repair, and migration execution.\n- On an unknown `format_version` or an unrecognised required capability: allow\n  `fsck`, diagnostics, backup, and explicit read-only inspection; report the\n  unsupported version/capability; block the mutating/publishing operations before\n  they acquire side effects (fail-closed).\n- Keep the ensure-registry for convergent check-then-act repairs. Do **not** build\n  the ordered ledger in this story — only the compatibility record + reader gate.\n  (An ordered once-only ledger is a separate future concern for non-convergent,\n  irreversible migrations.)\n\n## Scope\n\n- New module under `src/rebar/_store/` for the compatibility record + gate; wired\n  into the write/compact/push/reconcile/MCP-write/repair entry points.\n- `src/rebar/reducer/_version.py` — relate `format_version` to the existing\n  preserve-and-ignore `KNOWN_EVENT_TYPES` machinery (optional-additive stays\n  preserve-and-ignore; required-capability is the new fail-closed path).\n- `docs/migrations.md` — document the record, the fail-closed semantics, and the\n  optional-additive vs required-capability distinction.\n- Interface tests extending `tests/interfaces/contracts/test_event_schema_forward_compat.py`.\n- Out of scope: the ordered migration ledger; changing any existing event-replay\n  behaviour for currently-known types.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] A committed store compatibility record (`format_version` +\n  `required_capabilities`) is created at init and read by a gate function.\n- [ ] An **absent** record (pre-v1.0 store) is treated as legacy format version 0 /\n  compatible (pass-through, not blocked), and the ensure-registry idempotently writes\n  the record on the next covered write / init / fsck-repair / MCP-boot — verified by\n  a test that opens a record-less store with a v1.0 build and confirms it operates\n  and then carries the record (upgrade-in-place, no manual step).\n- [ ] The gate blocks mutation, compaction, repair, push, and reconcile before any\n  side effect only when the record is **present but incompatible** (unknown\n  `format_version` or unrecognised required capability) — demonstrated by Experiment\n  2A: an old-build reconcile/compact/write exits before producing a side effect\n  against a store requiring a new capability.\n- [ ] A rollback test (or documented analysis) confirms a pre-v1.0 binary encountering\n  the committed record leaves the store operable (record treated as ignored-unknown;\n  no parse-and-error, no destructive compaction/fsck interaction), or a\n  compensating-forward path is documented.\n- [ ] `fsck`, diagnostics, backup, and read-only inspection remain available under\n  an unknown version/capability and clearly report the unsupported version/capability.\n- [ ] Optional additive (unknown-but-not-required) events retain today's\n  preserve-and-ignore behaviour — the existing forward-compat contract tests still\n  pass, and a new test proves a *required* capability fails closed while an\n  *optional* additive event does not.\n- [ ] `docs/migrations.md` documents the compatibility record and the fail-closed\n  gate, including the deployment-order rationale (why the reader ships in v1.0).\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && make test` pass, and the change lands via the\n  Gerrit two-vote gate."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784045838005270001,"uuid":"5e15d2f8-2ee4-4d87-b33c-f27c180abbe4"}